Hey guys, couple of points on the topic from Charon middleware DV's perspective.

We currently send the `/eth/v1/validator/prepare_beacon_proposer` requests to the beacon node directly from Charon and swallow the requests Charon receives from the VC. This is done purely for simplicity, as the requests are not signed either way.

The `/eth/v1/builder/validators` from the Builder API we are forced to swallow, because the signed data includes the validator's pubkey. In our setup the VC has only a partial key and we aggregate the signatures from each DV peer. Here though, the signed data in a Charon cluster differs from peer to peer as VCs are signing over different pubkeys. So we cannot aggregate the signatures we receive from the VC. We do pre-sign the builder registrations at Charon level during cluster creation and just use those pre-signed messages, saved on disk.

That said, I see there are couple of proposals for moving forward here, but afaict none of them will be signing the data? This should be fine on our end. However, would it be an issue to use a validator index, rather than a pubkey as a key in the schema? For example looking at terence's PR https://github.com/OffchainLabs/prysm/pull/17124, to change it to:
```
{
  "version": 2,
  "proposer_config": {
    "12345": {
      "fee_recipient": "0x50155530FCE8a85ec7055A5F8b2bE214B3DaeFd3",
      ...
    }
  }
}
```


Also, non-DV related, but just my personal 2¢ on the per-validator builder configuration. We have some DV users that are utilising a 0x02 address per client of theirs. And I can definitely see those different clients of theirs having different preferences over builders, especially regulated and non-regulated.
